paper_title: The influences of temperature and microstructure on the tensile properties of a CoCrFeMnNi high-entropy alloy

graphs.title: Engineering stress–strain (fine-grained, d ≈ 4.4 μm) at six temperatures
graphs.description: Representative engineering stress–strain curves for the fine-grained CoCrFeMnNi alloy tested at 77, 293, 473, 673, 873, and 1073 K at an engineering strain rate of 10^-3 s^-1. Highest strength and ductility at 77 K; pronounced serrations at intermediate temperatures; a clear yield point with a small load drop is observed around 293–473 K; at 1073 K, the maximum stress is reached at low strain but failure occurs at >60% strain.
graphs.about_graph: Quasi-static uniaxial tension on recrystallized, single-phase fcc CoCrFeMnNi with grain size ≈4.4 μm. Curves show strong temperature dependence of yield strength, UTS, and elongation; the inset for 473 K highlights a small load drop after yielding. Test rate 10^-3 s^-1 and the six temperatures are annotated on the curves.

curves.curve_description: Highest yield and tensile strengths with large work-hardening; highest ductility among the six temperatures.
curves.about_curve: Cryogenic testing promotes strong work hardening and delays necking in this alloy.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Much higher flow stress and work hardening; largest uniform elongation.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, grain size, test rate, and engineering stress–strain axes.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.023–0.072.

curves.curve_description: Lower strengths than 77 K; significant work hardening; ductility lower than at 77 K.
curves.about_curve: Representative room-temperature response for FG condition.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Intermediate strength/ductility; no serrations as strong as 673 K.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same FG microstructure and test conditions.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.027–0.068.

curves.curve_description: Shows a well-defined yield point with a small load drop and serrations; strength lower than at 293 K.
curves.about_curve: Exhibits yield-point phenomenon and dynamic strain-aging-like serrations in FG material.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Distinct yield point and post-yield load drop; serrations more evident.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same axes, alloy, strain rate, and FG grain size.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.144–0.260.

curves.curve_description: Further reduced strength with pronounced serrations; FG ductility reaches a minimum in this range.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lowest ductility among FG curves despite modest stresses.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.129–0.205.

curves.curve_description: Low strengths and moderate ductility; serrations diminish relative to 673 K.
curves.about_curve: High-temperature weakening with reduced work hardening.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Among the lowest strengths before the 1073 K case.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.154–0.293.

curves.curve_description: Lowest stresses; peak reached at a few percent strain but failure occurs beyond 60% engineering strain.
curves.about_curve: Very low work hardening; extensive post-peak elongation.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lowest strength; unique early peak with long post-peak strain.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, FG microstructure, and axes.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.190–0.328.

graphs.title: Engineering stress–strain (coarse-grained, d ≈ 155 μm) at six temperatures
graphs.description: Representative engineering stress–strain curves for the coarse-grained CoCrFeMnNi alloy at 77, 293, 473, 673, 873, and 1073 K (10^-3 s^-1). Strength and ductility increase as temperature decreases; curves lack the fine-grained yield-point feature; failure typically occurs shortly after the maximum stress.
graphs.about_graph: Same testing protocol as Fig. 3a but with grain size ≈155 μm. CG and MG materials show nearly identical temperature trends in strength and ductility; no sharp yield point or load drop like the FG case.

curves.curve_description: Highest strength and ductility for CG; strong work hardening.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same CG microstructure, alloy, and axes.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.029–0.074.

curves.curve_description: Lower strength and ductility than 77 K; smooth yielding.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Intermediate properties; no serrated flow like FG.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.028–0.076.

curves.curve_description: Further reduced flow stress; moderate ductility.
curves.about_curve: Higher temperature weakens CG alloy with smooth flow.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lower stresses than 293 K; no sharp yield point.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.026–0.074.

curves.curve_description: Low strength with moderate strain to fracture; no obvious yield-point behavior.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Reduced flow stress vs. lower-T curves.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.193–0.314.

curves.curve_description: Very low flow stresses; ductility still significant but failure shortly after UTS.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.203–0.303.

curves.curve_description: Lowest strengths for CG; failure near the peak.
curves.about_curve: Very limited work hardening at the highest temperature.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Minimum flow stress and lowest work hardening.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, CG grains, and axes.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.113–0.189.

graphs.title: True stress–true strain (converted from Fig. 3a) up to UTS
graphs.description: True stress–true strain curves recalculated from the fine-grained engineering curves (Fig. 3a) up to the onset of geometric instability (UTS), shown for 77, 293, and 473 K. These reveal the larger work-hardening rate at 77 K and earlier approach to instability at higher temperatures.
graphs.about_graph: Same specimens and conditions as Fig. 3a; conversion performed up to the UTS point to avoid post-necking artifacts. Companion Fig. 12b shows dσ_t/dε_t vs σ_t and Considère criterion.

curves.curve_description: Highest true stresses and work-hardening rate; intersection with Considère line occurs at the highest strain.
curves.about_curve: Reflects cryogenic strengthening and delayed necking due to high work hardening.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Largest slope (work-hardening rate) and highest σ_t.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, FG grain size, and conversion method.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.031–0.076.

curves.curve_description: Intermediate true stresses and hardening; necking predicted at lower strain than 77 K.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lower σ_t and hardening than 77 K but higher than 473 K.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.021–0.070.

curves.curve_description: Lowest of the three in true stress and work-hardening rate; necking onset occurs at the smallest true strain.
curves.about_curve: Converted curve corresponding to a case with serrations in engineering data.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Minimum σ_t and hardening among the three temperatures.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same FG condition and conversion procedure.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.029–0.077.
